    "answer_id" : 38302207,
    "question_id" : 1671378,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java 8 you have some many operators to use, for instance <strong>limit</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>     /**\n * Operator that limit the total number of items emitted through the pipeline\n * Shall print\n * [1]\n * @throws InterruptedException\n */\n@Test\npublic void limitStream() throws InterruptedException {\n    List&lt;Integer&gt; list = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 1, 4, 2, 3)\n                               .stream()\n                               .limit(1)\n                               .collect(toList());\n    System.out.println(list);\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6622869,
      "reputation" : 607,
      "user_id" : 5113951,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a4c8812b6b552afd27e52d3184eceff0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Nacho Soriano",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5113951/nacho-soriano"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1494323127,
    "creation_date" : 1494323127,
    "answer_id" : 43866464,
    "question_id" : 1671378,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can do a casting. For example, if exists one method with this definition, and you know that this method is returning a List:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Collection&lt;String&gt; getStrings();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>And after invoke it, you need the first element, you can do it like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; listString = (List) getStrings();\nString firstElement = (listString.isEmpty() ? null : listString.get(0));\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2139684,
      "reputation" : 9851,
      "user_id" : 2019549,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 62,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/900a3735d55a0473c975ba9266bf0c68?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "cambunctious",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2019549/cambunctious"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1542389420,
    "creation_date" : 1542389420,
    "answer_id" : 53342724,
    "question_id" : 1671378,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Guava provides an <code>onlyElement</code> <code>Collector</code>, but only use it if you expect the collection to have exactly one element.</p>\n\n<pre><code>Collection&lt;String&gt; stringCollection = ...;\nString string = collection.stream().collect(MoreCollectors.onlyElement())\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you are unsure of how many elements there are, use <code>findFirst</code>.</p>\n\n<pre><code>Optional&lt;String&gt; optionalString = collection.stream().findFirst();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 17505775,
        "reputation" : 3167,
        "user_id" : 12695027,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/DsdZt.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Scratte",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12695027/scratte"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1585566505,
      "post_id" : 60927965,
      "comment_id" : 107795486,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Your choice of <code>List&lt;T&gt;</code> doesn&#39;t satisfy the condition that it should work for a <code>Collection&lt;String&gt;</code>, but of course that can be fixed using <code>Collection&lt;T&gt;</code>, with the additional change: <code>.map(Collection::stream)</code>."
    } ],
