    "answer_id" : 79477448,
    "question_id" : 1671378,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h1><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/SequencedCollection.html#getFirst()\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>SequencedCollection#getFirst</code></a></h1>\n<p>Starting with Java 21, <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/SequencedCollection.html#getFirst()\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>SequencedCollection#getFirst</code></a> can be used for a sequenced collection. <code>NoSuchElementException</code> is thrown if the collection is empty.</p>\n<p>For example, the implementation of <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html#getFirst()\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>List#getFirst</code></a> returns the result of calling <code>List#get(0)</code>.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>List&lt;String&gt; list = List.of(&quot;Foo&quot;, &quot;Bar&quot;);\nString str = list.getFirst();\nSystem.out.println(str); // Foo\n</code></pre>\n"
